  "text": "By the end of this section, you'll understand which allergens actually matter in your bread bakery, how to structure a changeover that prevents cross-contact, and why visual inspection alone will never be enough. Let's start with a principle that saves enormous wasted effort. Don't build allergen protocols for allergens you don't handle. No sesame on-site? No sesame changeover procedure needed? No tree nuts? Skip the tree nut protocol. Focus on what's real in your facility. In a standard bread bakery, your allergen reality looks like this. Wheat and gluten are your primary ingredient. They're in every product, on every surface, and in the air as flour dust. Wheat isn't typically your changeover concern because it's omnipresent. Soy is the hidden one. It's in your bread improvers, and it catches people out because nobody thinks of improver as a soy-containing ingredient. Check your specification sheets. Many improvers contain soya flour or soya lecithin. If you're running products with and without improver on the same lines, soy cross-contact is a real risk. Dairy comes through milk powder for enriched doughs, bun recipes, and speciality breads. If you alternate standard white bread and milk-enriched dough on the same mixer, that's a dairy changeover. Eggs appear in certain product lines, particularly enriched breads and egg wash applications. If you use liquid egg or egg powder, you need changeover protocols. Now the changeover process itself. Product sequencing is your first control. Run allergen-free products first, then products containing allergens. This minimizes residual allergen contaminating the next product. When you changeover, follow a clear documented process. First, line clearance. Remove all ingredients and packaging from the previous product. Every open bag, every container, every label. Nothing stays. Second, clean all product-contact surfaces. Your mixer bowl and agitator, hopper, dough divider, molder, provert trays, conveyor belts, and depositor nozzles. This isn't a quick wipe. It's a thorough clean following your allergen-specific SSOP. Third, validate the clean. This is where most bakeries fall short. Allergen proteins are invisible at the residue levels that matter. You can look at a mixer seal and see nothing. But there could be enough milk protein trapped in that gasket to trigger an allergic reaction. Visual inspection alone is never enough for allergen changeovers. Your worst case validation points are the areas where residues hide. Gaskets and seals on mixer lids. The gap between the agitator shaft and the mixer bowl. Depositor nozzle internals. Conveyor belt edges where dough gets pushed to the sides. Molder roller ends. These are dead spots where product accumulates and standard cleaning doesn't fully reach. Validation means analytical testing. Lateral flow devices for specific allergens, milk protein or soy protein tests applied to swabs from your worst case surfaces. You don't need to test every surface every time. But you need to have validated your changeover procedure at least once for each allergen equipment combination with periodic revalidation. Recap. Know your actual allergens. Wheat is everywhere. Soy hides in bread improvers. Dairy in milk powder. Eggs in certain lines. Don't build protocols for allergens you don't handle. Sequence allergen free products first. Changeover means full line clearance, thorough cleaning and analytical validation on worst case points. Gaskets, seals, nozzle internals and conveyor edges."
